lor=#6F6F6F>(1/5/04 5:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=990.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Communication Established!</span><hr size=1> I see, seems like a reasonable idea. Only down side is that, since it is, effectively, battery powered it is not entirely passive so you would only get so many clicks before the capacitor ran down. <br>
<br>
How much energy can you store in modern super capacitors?<br>
<br>
I don't know how this technology has advanced over the last few years but I have seen large 1F PSU caps for ICE systems that can store, allegedly, around 70-100 joule, however this is pretty poor compared to the performance of a standard Duracell (alkaline, non-rechargeable D cell) which can store, allegedly, more like around 90Kj (Damn, that seems rather a lot actually, have I done my math right? 1.5 Volts at 18 Ah???)<br>
<br>
As far as Thermal signatures are concerned, it wouldn't work for all missions but on a cold plannet there may be potential. <br>
<br>
