circling back to the &quot;tagging&quot; thread...<br>
<br>
I thought of using the supercaps due to their high power output. Batteries historically produce greater energy (watthours) but relatively low power (watts).<br>
<br>
I anticipated needing just a few RF &quot;clicks&quot; to triangulate the landing site.<br>
<br>
The newest supercaps ~do~ reach energy densities approaching that of a primary battery.<br>
<br>
In any event, by making the tag a combo of a primary battery charging the cap - essentially an RF strobe - (and at the expense of some added complexity) the &quot;pinger&quot; could run continuously, without needing a query signal.<br>
<br>
====<br>
<br>
I have also been thinking out your suggestion about the RTG.<br>
The Vikings carried 1000 watts (thermal) of RTGs each. That should have made a rather bright light in infrared, against a cold nightime Martain surface.<br>
Altho I am not a fan of Pu238, if one ~did~ use it, it may be useful in probe location.<br>
